g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Template Method design pattern might endanger the risk of...

g.text: The Template Method design pattern might endanger the risk of violating the Liskov Substitution Principle. ‘Hook operations’, located in the abstract template class, could have some default behavior that may be overridden by the concrete template classes. The behavior that is promised from the base contract could be tightened in its preconditions, weakened in its postconditions or invariants might be ‘overruled’. This could result in clients receiving unexpected behavior that might result in a failure later. Another aspect is that clients might require anticipation to handle that behavior. This in turn might cause the cyclomatic complexity of the code to ‘grow’ or additional maintenance cost for resolving a bug later. An example, replacing the base class implementation with an empty function. This violates the ‘invariant - rule’, a condition that can be stated true in the entire execution of a program. Clients may count on this invariant, but suddenly the contract of the base class is violated. This means the client can encounter unanticipated / unexpected results from the subclass implementation, that could be fatal.

g.title: Folded Corner.276
g.desc: The Template Method Pattern compliments the Open Closed Princ...

g.text: The Template Method Pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by allowing clients to subclass an algorithm and redefine its details. This enables stability and reusability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where the algorithm(s) are situated in their own class resulting in change and/or duplication. Stability, because the Template method can be redefined in its details without direct modification. This allows extending the code base with different variants of an algorithm, while ensuring stability of the production and test code. Existing, working algorithmic code remains untouched and cannot be ‘broken’ accidently. Test code does not need to change, because production code remains ‘untouched’. Reusability, because the logic in the base template function is shared across multiple concrete variants of the algorithm. Inheritance accomplishes this reusability aspect. In contrast, having separate algorithm invariants without a common base class, would mean that the structure and common logic is duplicated across the code base. This results in additional maintenance when the algorithm base (logic or structure) requires change. The constraining factor that the Template Method provides, in the execution sequence, enhances design intent and overcomes clients possibly introducing new structures that could potentially introduce undefined situations.

g.title: Folded Corner.285
g.desc: The Template Method pattern ensures code reusability and over...

g.text: The Template Method pattern ensures code reusability and overcomes code duplication. Different variants of an algorithm, defined on multiple places of our code base, might contain common logic and structure. In case the algorithm changes in that common part it requires modification on multiple places. The Template method extracts this common algorithm logic into a base class, defines the skeleton and let’s subclasses implement the varying parts. This reduces the overall maintenance cost.

g.title: Folded Corner.294
g.desc: The Template Method pattern ensures that the structure of an ...

g.text: The Template Method pattern ensures that the structure of an algorithm remains in tact. Subclasses can only change the details, but cannot change the execution sequence nor certain fundamental parts of the algorithm. This compliments a safety aspect. The sequence of an algorithm is defined once and is identical for all variants of that algorithm. This means subclasses cannot unintentionally re-order certain execution steps, that potentially could cause undefined behavior. Constraining introduces stability. The design is intentional and clients are promised a given base class contract. The sharing of this structure amongst the sub-classes adds-up to the reusability aspect of the pattern.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Template Method pattern supports changing the fine, granu...

g.text: The Template Method pattern supports changing the fine, granular details of an Algorithm without direct modification. In case an algorithm changes frequently in its details and/or different variants of an algorithm must be supported, then it might enhance code stability to allow subclasses to define this logic. The Template pattern defines a template method containing ‘Hook’, concrete and primitive operations. ‘Hook’ operations often define some default behavior in the base class and may be overridden by the respective subclasses. Concrete base operations cannot be overridden by the subclasses and belong to the invariant part of the base class and algorithm. Primitive operations, should be minimized, otherwise it might be ‘work-intensive’ for subclasses to use a certain algorithm. This often happens in case an algorithm is made too generic, and subclasses define most of it. A solution can be to split it in two different algorithms instead of forcing the variants of the algorithm to fit under a single base. Primitive operations are pure, abstract operations that must be implemented by the subclasses

g.title: Folded Corner.302
g.desc: The Template method pattern both entails the negative and pos...

g.text: The Template method pattern both entails the negative and positive side of the Open Closed principle (=OCP). The Template Method pattern realizes OCP via inheritance. Implementation is shared amongst several concrete variants of an algorithm, resulting in no change in the core logic of the algorithm in case a new variant is introduced. The downside of inheritance, in case of the Template method pattern, is the additional form of indirection towards the details of the algorithm. This has negative impact on debuggability and navigability of the code. The Template design pattern should be used in case of frequent change in the algorithmic logic, code duplication exists across certain algorithms or it is likely that more variants of algorithm will be introduced. In all other cases the pattern only adds complexity and should be avoided.
